title: TAZ5 Dual Extruder V2 Filament Guide Bracket

description.text:
Remixed from a tutorial posted by KelVarnson on the Lulzbot forum page, this modified bracket keeps filament straight as it enters the extruder. I was having all sorts of issues with the Taz5 jamming especially when printing PLA. I started to realize that as the extruder gets to a certain height the filament becomes bent as the extruder tries to grab it.

I modified the bracket given in the tutorial here: https://forum.lulzbot.com/viewtopic.php?f=36&t=3319, essentially making the mounting nut slot a little longer, cutting the profile down so that you can get your fingers underneath still. As well the filament thru holes and teflon tube holes were a little tight and I needed to clean them up with a drill, these allow it to just fit.

This is a recreation of a puzzle from the 1980s called Panex. It is very hard to find originals of this puzzle now. The puzzle gained some notoriety for its extreme difficulty. Although it looks like the Tower of Hanoi, the ten piece version required over 31,000 moves to complete. I suggest starting with a six piece version, which takes only 881 moves to complete.

For a puzzle with two sets of six pieces, you will need one upper and one lower piece, and two sets of pieces. I suggest printing the upper and lower in one colour, and then the two sets of pieces in different colours otherwise you will have an extremely hard time solving the puzzle! The Panex puzzle came in two versions, silver and gold, where the silver had markings on it showing where the pieces went but the gold didn't. Given even the six piece puzzles takes 881 moves, I suggest not starting with the gold pieces (sixpiece_gold.stl), but just the sixpiece.stl. The sliding pieces print in two halves. The pieces that narrow go on the back of the upper, as shown in the last figure. I printed the one in the photos in PLA on an Ultimaker. There are also complete printing plants for six, eight and ten pieces if you want to experiment, and the SCAD source for the curious. A recent paper on the complexity of the solution can be found here. The six piece solution takes 881 moves, eight piece 5,359 and the ten piece is predicted to take 31537 moves (which has been confirmed here). The reason the puzzle is difficult is shown in the last but one image: the yellow piece on the right and the red piece in the middle will not slide any further down the slots.

description.text:
Here is a switch mount for a Mini Lathe with an autostop I designed (see 2nd photo).
I am putting this out here but I realize it is a very specific application and probably not of much use to others.
The stop is spring loaded and has a clamping effect. It holds very well and is easy to adjust.
The photos at the bottom were failed prints but work for showing how it's put together. The final product is much better quality but I forgot to take pictures before assembling it.

See photos. Print the two parts. Screw a 2 and 1/2 inch 8-32 machine screw into the smaller part (I used epoxy as a thread locker). Cut the head off the screw and guide it through the hole in the larger part aligning the "tab" with the "slot".
Drop a spring over the exposed threads and fasten a nut to the end. Tighten the nut to get needed holding force. If threads are exposed at this point they can be cut off. Mount the switch with 1/2 inch 4-40 screws and blind nuts.

description.text:
This is a two part case of an Inkbird temperature controller. It's compatible with the ITC-2000 and the ITC-1000, although the former only controls one relay. You can use the second hole to wire up a straight outlet that's not controlled by the thermostat if you have an ITC-2000.

Measurements are for:

  • this input power socket and switch and
  • these output power sockets

You also need four wood screws or self-tapping sheet metal screws (about 40mm and 3mm diameter) - I used #4 wood screws 1.5 inches long.

Drill out the screw holes if necessary.
Wire up the electronics, leaving some cable slack for the outlets.
Push in the Inkbird and power socket into the respective cutouts.
Insert the sensor cable into its cutout from the outside and secure it with a knot inside.
Screw in all cables into the right terminals.
Let the two outlets dangle outside their respective cutout.
Put the upper half on the lower half and slowly work it down until it's closed
Screw in the four top screws and the two screws for the power socket.
Push in the two outlets until you hear it click.
Add rubber feet if you like.

gives themselves lead poisoning, etc.

and air vent chimney. If you keep pouring metal until close to top
of funnel, you will exert more pressure on the metal filling the actual
mold and achieve a casting with better definition and fewer artifacts.
You will have to remove the excess metal with hacksaw and use a
file to smooth the base, but should provide a much more satisfactory
result than open topped v1 mold.

I tried to make it as thick as possible, to minimize breaking it while tightening the rod.
It should work for both M8 and 5/16" threaded rods.
The part where the rod fits has 7.6mm outer diameter. IT NEEDS to be threaded. I used a short screw to make the threads.

IT'S NOT SYMMETRICAL. The marks within the model indicates the screw position. If you don't place them like this, they will touch the Z Motor Mount.
 
 
The one that uses 2 screws is dimensionally similar to the stock version. I made the other one because I had room for a longer coupler, making it a bit more stiffer. Both of them work great.

.STP files uploaded =)
Enjoy!

title: Orca Series linear bearing lm8uu x-carriage

description.text:
Finally! There it is, a linear bearing x-carriage for the Orca 0.3 (and possibly also 0.2, please report if you used it succesfully on your 0.2). I wanted to create the most simple solution to fix the x-carriage problems on the orca 0.3. On my printer the x-carriage does not fit too optimal. Also, the x-carriage is hard and time consuming to assemble. Furthermore it doesn't even fit, because it hits the metal on both bottom sides. This new re-designed x-carriage only consists of one plastic item. The lm8uu bearings will snugly fit in the holders and on the smooth rods. And last but not least, you can easily fit the x-belt in the holder. I did 2 tries now to print the carriage, but both times I had some problems with my printer. I will try to print again tomorrow. Keep yourself posted on my profiles and thingies on thingiverse. As soon as this bearing is finished I will start working on a y-axis linear bearing and also an z-axis linear bearing! BTW I bought the cheapest linear bearings from ebay:
http://www.ebay.com/itm/290626116456

Update version 5:
  • made the LM8UU holders a bit longer
  • reinforced the belt clamp by 3mm
    • Update version 4:
  • belt holder a bit higher (belts fit perfectly without screws)
  • LM8UU holder made just a bit wider
  • holes for the smoothed rods made a bit larger
  • removed the holes for the middle 2 bolts (not needed)
  • made some space for the back bolts so they can be attached
  • some reinforcement added for the connecting bars
  • Print the x-carriage with your best profile
  • Snugly fit 4 lm8uu bearings inside the holders
  • Disassemble your original x-carriage
  • Attach the new x-carriage to the metal platform (make sure the belt holder is on the right side) tighten all 4 screws. Optionally including the fan holder on top.
  • Attach the motor back on top

description.text:
Sony AZ1 VR Action Cam provides everything to make video underwater, except everything is blurred due to the standard lens of the waterproof case.
I've designed this small adapter for a 38mm flat lens you can order for few $ on Ebay or Aliexpress (search for "lens JYC 40mm").

Rafts:

No

Doesn't Matter

I've printed it in black PLA with 3 layers of marine varnish to avoid any dissolution in salted water. It's been working perfectly for months. But as suggested, I recommend ABS or any other water-compatible material.

comments.text: I would not suggest anyone print this with PLA, if you plan on using it a lot. There is no way to guarantee the water-tightness of PLA after you expose it to the elements. ABS, PET-T, PET-G, polycarbonate are all better choices.
comments.author: WheresWaldo

comments.text:
Hello WheresWaldo,
Agree with you it would be better with anything else than PLA (I've already said that in the description). I spent 2 weeks diving at 4-5 meters deep during hours and I did not have any issue. The marine varnish works well on my boat models and on this piece too (polyurethane-based, not water-based).
Concerning the fastening, you're right. For my first prototype, I used Black Sikaflex bought from a shipchandler. It worked well but I found it too soft when temperature was above 25°C. So now I use B7000 glue which works perfectly. The best would be to use specific adhesive washers (like 3M ones) but they cost very much unfortunatly.

After adjusting the tension on the X-axis belt for the zillionth time (to loose = lash, to tight = motor skip), I designed this little tension clamp.
The clamp consists of 2 parts: one goes onto the carriage with the original 2x40mm bolts. The other part gets clamped on the belt with 2x20mm M4 bolts and 2 nuts. The 2 parts are joined with an 55mm M4 bolt and M4 nylok.
After putting everything together, its a matter of tensioning a single bolt to modify the tension on the belt.
No more unscrewing and re-fastening over and over again!
Note: The orientation of the belt with this design is for the alternative X-axis where the teeth of the belt point inwards.
Note 2: Photos of all parts plus mounted on the Mendel will come soon.

• Print all 4 parts
  • Put the base plate on the carriage
  • Hold the end of the belt over the notches in the plate
  • Add clamp and insert bolts
  • Insert nuts into back plate of floating clamp
  • Add belt between both parts; make sure you are in reach of whatever bolt you will use to tension the belt (not too far, not too close)
  • Add both 20mm bolts (they should not stick out the end of the back plate)
  • Insert 55mm M4 bolt + washer into base block
  • Hold nylok and screw 55mm into floating block
    • Once they are joined, it might not be necessary to hold the nylok when adjusting the tension a little bit.

description.text:
Many velomobiles use a plastic coupling part to form a universal joint. Over time, this part wears and that introduces play into the steering. Initially, the play can be eliminated by merely tightening the bolts which hold the steering coupling in place, but as more wear develops this will no longer work.

This part replaces the original steering coupler in a Sinner Mango or Velomobiel Quest or Strada (and quite possibly other models too), removing the slop from the steering which results from using a worn steering coupler. In the first photo, the original very worn part is on the right, the newly 3D printed equivalent on the left.

Note: This is currently experimental. I have 3D printed a part like this for use on my own velomobile and am currently testing it. Because the part is in compression due to the two bolts which run through it, I think it will be strong enough even though a chunk of 3D printed plastic is not as strong as the original milled and drilled solid plastic version of the part. At 300 km, there is no apparent wear on my steering block. It is still performing well.

Another warning: It is not known yet whether it is safe to use a 3D printed part in this position. It may fail. If you print your own and yours fails, then you have done this at your own risk. I cannot be held responsible. For me this is an experiment.

Find other parts for velomobiles and recumbents in our webshop: http://www.dutchbikebits.com/recumbent-velomobile-parts

description.text: I've been using the Prusa Mendel Filament Spool Holder for a couple of years now (I should; I designed it!), but I've been using a box wrench whenever I needed to change out filament reels. I belatedly had the idea of making this knob (which press-fits onto a 5/16" nylock nut) to make it possible to do filament changes using just bare hands. It's a good refinement, and makes me a bit more willing to, e.g., change filament to get a different color.

(1) Print the attached STL file. Sand as necessary; I spent a bit of time on this since it's something I'll be gripping with my bare hand. (2) Use a bench vise or diagonal pliers to press-fit the knob onto a standard 5/16 Nylock nut. The "top" of the nut (the end with the nylon insert) goes into the knob first. (Note: It may also fit an 8mm Nylock for those who have an all-metric Mendel; I didn't try it). (3) Screw the knob onto the shaft of the Filament Spool Holder in place of the original bare nut, adjusting as needed to allow the spool to feed easily but not unwind wildly. (4) Put that wrench that's been sitting next to your printer back in your tool box and leave it there.

description.text: Want to make ice (or other cast substance) in the shape of a sphere? Now you can!

Print both halve of the mold, screw them together, fill with water, and freeze.  
Bearing in mind that ice expands when it freezes (and exerts a surprising amount of force while doing so) I recommend printing with at least three, if not four, perimeters to avoid the possibility of the ice causing delamination in the mold. The mold will print just fine at .3mm layer height, but lower layer heights will produce a finer mold.  
A note about food safety - Neither ABS nor PLA are considered food safe. I wouldn't recommend using this mold for ice if you print it in either of those plastics. Nylon should be food safe, but there is no consensus about the safety of nylon extruded through consumer hotends. Any printed mold is also likely to contain many small grooves which may provide an environment for mold/fungus/other unpleasant things to grow in over time.  
Basically what I'm saying is: Make ice in this at your own risk. I'm willing to take that risk myself, but you have to make your own decision on the matter.  
Customizable variables:  
top_or_bottom - The same .scad file will produce both halves of the mold, modify this variable to choose which half to produce.  
wall_thickness - The model is optimized for printing with .42mm thick walls. It should (probably) print with different wall thicknesses, but changing this variable will produce a model optimized for printing at different wall thicknesses.  
fudge_factor - This variable changes the gap between the connection ball and the connection groove. If the connection is too tight, increase this value.  
fudge_factor2 - This variable changes the gap between the inner and outer mold halves. You want this to be as small as possible while still allowing the halves to fit in order to prevent the mold from leaking at the joint.  
mold_size - This variable sets the size of the object to be created in the mold.  
fineness - This variable changes the number of rendered faces on the round parts of the mold. Increase to make the mold smoother, decrease to reduce the number of faces on the model.

description.text: I wanted to have my Prusa a little more secure while traveling plus it looks neat. This is a DXF to laser cut in 1/4 plywood (I used oak). The Prusa is held down using four brackets that fit over my bottom side rods (5/16 or 8mm). I covered both sides with contact cork to help with vibrations and to keep from scratching the table it sits on.

Laser cut base in 1/4" plywood (I used a higher quality oak plywood because it doesn't warp as much). I covered both sides in contact paper backed cork. The mounting brackets fit around the bottom side threaded rods and are secured to the board using M4 screws. I used oval head tapered screws so they would sit flush with the cork (lowes part# 880750, M4-0.70 x 16).   
Print 4 of the brackets. The dxf also has some holes pre-cut for the screws (6.75" apart for my rod spacing).

title: Replacement knob for LG gas range

description.text:
Imagine a gas range that has nice-looking knobs that break in about a year, and standard replacement knobs don't fit. Replacement knobs are available for over USD $100 each - that doesn't make sense for a range you can get on clearance for around $600 new.  
These knobs should fit tightly on the knob stems and should be fairly easy to clean.

Prints best in ABS plastic. The fit on the knob stems may be a bit tight but should go in 10mm. Printing in ABS will end up with warping on the back side of the knob but this should not significantly impact appearance nor should it interfere with functionality.

comments.text: I'd gone through 5 replacement knobs for my LG EBZ37189611, which kept breaking - once the fitting cracks, they fall off, and gradually crack more until they hardy stay on the stove. Some would also delaminate (they're not truly stainless steel, that's just the color of the finish (for example see: https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00AH5ZU2G/) Some users suggested adding a washer to the knobs to reinforce them, I decided to try printing these before attempting the washer solution on another set. So far, so good - just requires extracting the metal spacer from the old knobs and seating the spacers in the new plastic ones (if you don't do this, you'll be very disappointed). I used 3dhubs.com - just download the files here and upload them there, then you'll get estimates from vendors (some of which may be local).
comments.author: jidulberger

comments.text: If this works, that'll be great.  I found replacement knobs on Amazon for less than half what LG charges, but that's still  $125 for the set of 5. The OEM spec says they're stainless, but that borders on false advertising. After a couple of years of use heat from the oven is causing the "stainless" foil to delaminate leaving bubbles on the already broken knobs. So, $125 for new knobs that will be in the exact same condition as the old ones in a year or so, or print some with silver or black filament? Simple tool to focus a K40 laser cutter. Place the part labeled BED> towards the bed and the other part over the X axis gantry. Prop up your workpiece until it touches the bottom of the tool.

Distance was measured by placing a piece of cardboard in the bed at an angle and finding the sharpest point after cutting a long rectangle. Focus distance may need to be adapted for your particular machine.

CorelDraw and SVG files are included. When engraving then cutting make sure to select the invisible white square in the upper left of the file - this ensures the engrave and cut operations are aligned.

I was surprised that the best distance for cutting was quite a bit higher than the bed!

comments.text: I've recently purchased a K40 and it looks like you've been discovering its little oddities too. My bed was so far out of alignment I ended up making 3D printed supports to level it up. If you've not discovered the entire y carriage may also be quite badly out of alignment, mine runs out almost 5mm back to front so I've had level the bed from the head x axis carriage. Once I've got it close I engrave a target at each corner and tweak the level from that. Mine can now cut 6mm ply in one or two passes at around 15-20mA. I made a similar guide as your just a few weeks ago and initially used the sloping board idea to get the focus right.
